    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Is Alcohol the Culprit in Violence?</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Travis Youman letter on Caroline Knapp's June 21 article holds alcohol does not cause violence, but inflates drinkers' sense that they will not get caught</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Drunk and Out of Control,'' by Caroline Knapp (Op-Ed, June 21):</p>
        <p>When drunk, a person still has the same morality he has when sober, even if when drunk he has an inflated sense of security that he won't get caught. The people who blame drinking for their actions would commit those very same acts if they were sure there would be no consequences.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Drunk and Out of Control,'' by Caroline Knapp (Op-Ed, June 21):</p>
        <p>When drunk, a person still has the same morality he has when sober, even if when drunk he has an inflated sense of security that he won't get caught. The people who blame drinking for their actions would commit those very same acts if they were sure there would be no consequences.</p>
        <p>It's not the alcohol; it's the basic lack of respect for other people that's to blame.</p>
        <p>TRAVIS YOUMAN  Cortlandt Manor, N.Y.  June 21, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
